{"key":"post-8511079","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8511079</id>\n<content>Tiny or non-existant caps are a sure sign of insufficient light.&amp;nbsp; Incandescent is the worst possible light source since it's 'red' with a color temperature of only 3,000 Kelvin.&amp;nbsp; Mycelium pins best with lights that are at the blue end of the spectrum, with a color temperature of around 6,500 K.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, incandescent lamps put out 90% of the energy they consume as heat, compounding your problem.&amp;nbsp; Fluorescent tubes put out 90% of the energy they consume as light, which is where you're lacking.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Replace the light bulb with fluorescent lights.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;85% humidity is too low for cakes(or even cased substrates for that matter).&amp;nbsp; Get rid of the silly outdated pop bottle tek and use perlite.&amp;nbsp; You'll get 99% humidity.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;An hour of light, especially the wrong type of light, is not nearly enough, despite advice noobs will give you to the contrary.&amp;nbsp; Get flourescent lamps and run them roughly 12 hours per day.&amp;nbsp; Mist as required.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8511095</next>\n<prev>8511041</prev>\n<first>8511041</first>\n<last>8512707</last>\n<when>1213208837</when>\n<utime>06/11/08 09:27 PM</utime>\n</post>"}